EQUINE INFECTIOUS ANEMIA - USA (03): (MASSACHUSETTS, FLORIDA)
*************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

In this posting:
[1] Massachusetts
[2] Florida

******
[1] Massachusetts
Date: Wed 1 Sep 2010
Source: The Telegram [edited]
<http://www.telegram.com/article/20100901/NEWS/9010365/1003/NEWS03>


State agriculture officials said they will remove from the farm of a
local veterinarian a horse that may be infected with the potentially
dangerous equine infectious anemia [EIA].

The Massachusetts Department of Agricultural Resources last month
[August 2010] ordered the veterinarian to transfer Nora, a miniature
horse, to a research facility licensed by the federal Department of
Agriculture over concerns that the animal has the EIA disease.

State authorities said they would remove and euthanize the horse if
the veterinarian did not comply.

The state had issued the order to remove the animal by 26 Aug 2010
but officials extended the deadline until 5 p.m. yesterday [31 Aug
2010]. Catherine Williams, a spokesman for the Department of
Agricultural Resources, said last night that the veterinarian did not
comply by the latest deadline. She said state officials will now
seize the mare, although she added she didn't know when that action
will be taken.

Ms Williams noted that, since the deadline extension, officials have
been in contact with the veterinarian through his legal counsel.

This doctor owns a number of miniature horses on his 200-acre [81 ha]
property. He has maintained that, though the horse has been exposed
to EIA, the animal showed no signs of the disease after being tested twice.

The veterinarian said Nora may carry protective antibodies to EIA and
should be allowed to live because she is valuable to biomedical
research. He could not be reached for comment last night.

[Byline: Bronislaus B Kush]

--
