[There are a couple of key issues here: the horse has not been proven
to have the disease, as the article says "may" have the disease.
Therefore, what right does the state have to seize an animal if they
are not certain the animal has the disease? If the animal is proven
to have the disease, why can the owner not self quarantine? Most
states allow such quarantine, provided no animals leave the property.
Why is the state of Massachusetts appearing to be unreasonable here?
If some one from the state veterinarian's office would care to
respond, we would appreciate it. - Mod.TG]

[The state of Massachusetts can be located on the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the US at
<http://healthmap.org/r/05ig>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

******
[2] Florida
Date: Wed 1 Sep 2010
Source: TCPalm [edited]
<http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2010/sep/01/fellsmere-woman-hid-horses-serious-illness-state/>


A Fellsmere woman used an elaborate ruse to cover up her horse's rare
communicable disease that, left unchecked, potentially could have
spread through Florida's horse industry, a state Department of
Agriculture spokesman said Wednesday [1 Sep 2010].

The woman was arrested Tuesday [31 Aug 2010] on a charge of willfully
violating a state law that required reporting that her horse, Dolly,
had equine infectious anemia -- an incurable virus that causes fever,
anemia, and occasionally death, state spokesman Terry McElroy said.

State tests have confirmed the woman's other horse also has the
disease, which is usually spread by flies biting one infected horse
and carrying the blood to another, McElroy said. Both horses were
taken from the woman and her husband's ranch and are in a
state-approved quarantine facility in South Florida.

Eventually, the woman will have to decide whether to keep the horses
in her own quarantine or put them to death -- an alternative court
documents say she was trying to avoid by giving a false name,
addresses, and phone numbers.

The real estate agent even used a co-worker's e-mail account in Palm
Bay to disguise herself, arrest records show. That's because,
according to court documents, the owner's 5-year-old granddaughter
wanted to ride Dolly, a 28-year-old mare, in competition. [The
granddaughter never did ride the horse in competition], McElroy said.

It is the 1st known criminal case of its type in recent history in a
state that has an estimated 500 000 horses. About 140 000 Florida
horses are tested annually for the disease. Usually, at the most, one
horse has the virus, McElroy said.

State agricultural officials began tracking down the owner after she
-- using her maiden name -- had East Coast Equine veterinarian clinic
in Vero Beach take a blood sample on 24 Jun 2010 because she
suspected her horse had the virus.

On 14 Jul 2010 a state lab in Kissimmee [Florida] confirmed the illness.

Then state veterinarian John Crews found the owner's name, address,
and phone number given to East Coast Equine were wrong. Department of
Agriculture workers unsuccessfully checked property and driver's
license records and asked around the Fellsmere community.

Finally the agency assigned one of its detectives, who found an
e-mail address given to East Coast Equine belonged to one of the
owner's co-workers in Palm Bay. The detective tracked her down at her
ranch in late July [2010] and was told "she used the alias in order
to buy time for Dolly since she believed that the horse would be
euthanized," according to the detective's record in court files.

The horse's owner is out of the Indian River County Jail under a USD
7500 bail. Her next scheduled court appearance is 9 a.m. 20 Oct 2010
in Indian River Circuit Court.

[Byline: Elliott Jones]

